## Implementation

As a first step, I would create a new React project using the latest version of React and Three.js. Here is how you can do it:

```bash
npx create-react-app chat-app
cd chat-app
npm install three
```

Then, I will design the chat interface including features like message bubbles, user typing indicators, etc. For this part, we might need to leverage Three.js for some 3D animations if needed. This can be a complex task and requires good understanding of both React and Three.js. 

Next, I would implement real-time messaging functionality using WebSockets. A server-side setup is required here as WebSocket connections need to be persistent and bidirectional. Here's an example of how you can set up a WebSocket server in Node.js:

```javascript
const WebSocket = require('ws');

const wss = new WebSocket.Server({ port: 8080 });

wss.on('connection', (ws) => {
    ws.on('message', (message) => {
        console.log(`Received message: ${message}`);
        // Broadcast the received message to all connected clients
        wss.clients.forEach((client) => {
            if (client !== ws && client.readyState === WebSocket.OPEN) {
                client.send(message);
            }
        });
    });
});
```

For the AI agent, we can use libraries like Dialogflow or Rasa to understand human language and generate responses. These libraries provide APIs for intent classification, entity recognition, and response generation. Here's how you can integrate Dialogflow into your chat application:

```javascript
const dialogflow = require('@google-cloud/dialogflow');
// Instantiate a new session by using the `detectIntent` function
const sessionClient = new dialogflow.SessionsClient();
const sessionPath = sessionClient.sessionPath('your-project-id', 'your-session-id');

const request = {
    session: sessionPath,
    queryInput: {
        text: {
            text: 'Hello from the other side',
            languageCode: 'en-US',
        },
    },
};

sessionClient.detectIntent(request)
    .then(responses => {
        const result = responses[0].queryResult;
        console.log(`  Query: ${result.queryText}`);
        console.log(`  Response: ${result.fulfillmentText}`);
        // Here you can send the AI agent's response to all connected clients via WebSocket
    })
    .catch(err => {
        console.error('ERROR:', err);
    });
```

Finally, we need to integrate the AI agent with our chat application and handle user authentication if needed. This is a complex task that requires good understanding of both React (for UI) and your chosen AI library/API (Dialogflow). 

I would write tests for each part of my codebase using testing libraries like Jest or Mocha in order to ensure they work as expected before deploying the application. Here's a simple example:

```javascript
import { sum } from './sum'; // Let's assume we have a function 'sum' in sum.js file

test('adds 1 + 2 to equal 3', () => {
    expect(sum(1, 2)).toBe(3);
});
```

Finally, I would set up a Continuous Integration (CI) pipeline using tools like Jenkins, GitLab CI or Github Actions to automate my testing and deployment processes. This can be complex depending on the complexity of your application but it's crucial for code quality assurance. Here is an example of how you can use GitHub Actions:

```yaml
name: Node CI
on: [push]
jobs:
  build:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
    steps:
    - uses: actions/checkout@v2
    - name: Use Node.js
      uses: actions/setup-node@v1
      with:
        node-version: 12
    - run: npm ci
    - run: npm run build --if-present
    - run: npm test
```

I would also document the chat application including its architecture, APIs, data flow, security considerations etc. This is crucial for future maintenance and troubleshooting. Here's an example of what this might look like:

```markdown
# Chat Application Architecture

## Components
- Frontend (React)
- Backend (Node.js, WebSocket Server)
- AI Agent Integration (Dialogflow API)

## APIs
